The OSI Model
What is the OSI Model?

The Open Systems Interconnection (OSI) Model is a conceptual framework that explains how data travels from one device to another across a network.

It consists of 7 layers, where each layer performs a specific function before passing the data to the next layer.

The 7 OSI Layers
Layer 7 - Application
Closest layer to the user.
Provides network services to applications.
Responsible for user interaction with network services.

Examples

HTTP / HTTPS
FTP
SMTP
DNS
Layer 6 - Presentation

Responsible for formatting data so different systems can understand it.

Functions include:

Encryption
Decryption
Compression
Character encoding
Data formatting
Layer 5 - Session

Manages communication sessions between devices.

Responsibilities:

Starts sessions
Maintains sessions
Ends sessions

Examples include keeping users logged into websites or maintaining video conference sessions.

Layer 4 - Transport

Responsible for end-to-end communication.

Functions:

Segmentation
Error recovery
Flow control
Reliability

Protocols:

TCP (Reliable)
UDP (Fast but unreliable)

Transport layer uses port numbers to identify applications.

Layer 3 - Network

Responsible for moving packets between different networks.

Functions:

Logical addressing
Routing
Path selection

Uses:

IP Addresses
Routers
Layer 2 - Data Link

Responsible for communication on the local network.

Functions:

MAC addressing
Frame creation
Error detection

Devices:

Switches
NICs

Uses MAC addresses instead of IP addresses.

Layer 1 - Physical

Responsible for transmitting raw bits.

Includes:

Ethernet cables
Fiber optics
Wireless signals
Electrical and optical signals

Devices:

Hubs
Repeaters
Cables
Encapsulation

As data travels down the OSI model:

Application Data

↓

Segments (Layer 4)

↓

Packets (Layer 3)

↓

Frames (Layer 2)

↓

Bits (Layer 1)

The receiving device performs de-encapsulation, reversing the process.

Mnemonic

Top → Bottom

All People Seem To Need Data Processing

Bottom → Top

Please Do Not Throw Sausage Pizza Away

Networking Devices

Networking devices connect computers and direct traffic efficiently.

Hub

A hub is a basic networking device.

Characteristics:

Broadcasts data to every connected device
No intelligence
Half-duplex
Causes collisions
Operates at Layer 1

Not commonly used today.

Switch

A switch intelligently forwards data.

Characteristics:

Learns MAC addresses
Sends traffic only to the intended device
Reduces collisions
Improves performance
Operates at Layer 2

Most common device inside LANs.

Router

Routers connect different networks.

Responsibilities:

Route packets
Connect LANs to WANs
Choose best path
Separate broadcast domains

Operates at Layer 3.

Firewall

A firewall controls network traffic.

Functions:

Allow traffic
Block traffic
Filter ports
Filter protocols
Security enforcement

Can be hardware or software.

Wireless Access Point (WAP)

Provides wireless connectivity.

Responsibilities:

Connect Wi-Fi devices
Bridge wireless devices to wired networks

Does not perform routing by itself.

Modem

Converts signals between:

ISP connection
Home network

Common examples:

DSL
Cable
Fiber ONT
Bridge

Connects two LAN segments.

Functions:

Filters traffic
Reduces collisions

Largely replaced by switches.

Repeater

Repeater regenerates weak signals.

Purpose:

Extend cable distance
Improve signal quality

Layer 1 device.

Gateway

A gateway connects different types of networks or protocols.

Examples:

Internet gateway
Protocol translation

Often refers to the default gateway (router).

Networking Functions

Networking functions describe how devices communicate efficiently across networks.

Bandwidth

Bandwidth is the maximum amount of data that can be transmitted over a network in a given amount of time.

Measured in:

Mbps
Gbps

Higher bandwidth allows more data to be transmitted.

Throughput

Throughput is the actual amount of data successfully transferred.

Usually lower than bandwidth due to:

Congestion
Errors
Hardware limitations
Latency

Latency is the delay between sending and receiving data.

Measured in milliseconds (ms).

Lower latency is better.

Jitter

Jitter is the variation in latency over time.

High jitter causes:

Choppy voice calls
Laggy video meetings
Poor streaming
Packet Loss

Occurs when packets never reach their destination.

Causes include:

Congestion
Damaged cables
Weak Wi-Fi
Hardware failures

Results:

Slow applications
Buffering
Connection problems
Duplex
Half-Duplex
Send OR receive
Not simultaneously

Example:

Walkie-talkies

Full-Duplex
Send AND receive simultaneously

Example:

Modern Ethernet networks

Collision Domain

A collision occurs when two devices transmit simultaneously.

Switches create separate collision domains for each port, greatly reducing collisions.

Broadcast Domain

Broadcast traffic is sent to every device within the same network.

Routers separate broadcast domains.

MTU (Maximum Transmission Unit)

The largest packet size that can be transmitted without fragmentation.

Standard Ethernet MTU:

1500 bytes

Quality of Service (QoS)

QoS prioritizes important traffic.

Examples:

Voice calls
Video conferencing
Gaming traffic

Ensures critical traffic experiences less delay.

Key Takeaways
The OSI Model explains how data moves through seven networking layers.
Switches use MAC addresses to forward traffic within a LAN.
Routers use IP addresses to connect different networks.
Firewalls filter traffic to improve security.
Bandwidth is maximum capacity, while throughput is actual performance.
Latency, jitter, and packet loss directly affect network quality.
QoS helps prioritize important network traffic.
Understanding these concepts forms the foundation for networking and cybersecurity.
